{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "Many critical medical facilities are minimally prepared for disasters.", "abstract": "News Analysis; concerns about readiness of American health care providers during emergencies have been widespread, particularly in wake of disasters like Hurricane Katrina, yet current federal rules do not require any form of preparation for major emergencies by critical medical facilities; federal rule that would emergency preparedness condition for participation in Medicare and Medicaid, potentially impacting some 68,000 health care providers, has been stalled by unexpectedly lengthy Office of Management and Budget review. ", "section_name": "Sunday Review", "print_page": "7", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "Sheri", "role": "reported", "lastname": "FINK", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}], "original": "By SHERI FINK"}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/14/sunday-review/can-health-care-providers-afford-to-be-ready-for-disaster.html", "lead_paragraph": "Many critical medical facilities are minimally prepared for disasters.", "headline": {"print_headline": "Can Hospitals Afford to Be Ready for Disaster?", "main": "Can Health Care Providers Afford to Be Ready for Disaster?", "content_kicker": "News Analysis", "kicker": "News Analysis"}, "_id": "56bf8af638f0d86136858b34", "word_count": "1101", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2016/02/14/opinion/sunday/14fink/14fink-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2016/02/14/opinion/sunday/14fink/14fink-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 564, "url": "images/2016/02/14/opinion/sunday/14fink/14fink-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2016/02/14/opinion/sunday/14fink/14fink-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "564"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "image"}, {"height": 75, "url": "images/2016/02/14/opinion/sunday/14fink/14fink